    Date: 5 Dec 89 02:38:18 GMT
    From: dboyes@rice.edu  (David Boyes)


    There's been much discussion about POP servers for 4.3BSD-derived
    systems; has anyone implemented a POP server for Sys V.3
    machines, specifically a SGI Personal Iris? One of our science
    departments would like to use the Iris (their only Unix machine)
    as a POP server for a herd of PCs and Macs, but (alas) the Iris
    is fiercely SVR3 and can't compile all these wonderful BSD
    servers.

I don't know from POP, but lots of BSD-ish things can easily be compiled
on SGI using -I/usr/include/bsd -lsun -lbsd.  See the INTRO(3) man page.
Irix has most of the interesting BSD kernel features grafted on to it.

    There's probably enough interest for anyone posessing such a
    beast to post to the group at large; if you disagree, tell me
    about your server in private mail.

    As always, thanks in advance.

    David Boyes
    Rice University
    dboyes@rice.edu
    -- 
    David Boyes      "... no love was left; All Earth was but one thought - and
    dboyes@rice.edu   that was death Immediate and inglorious; and the pang of
		      of famine fed upon all entrails - men Died and their bones
		      were tombless as their flesh ..."  - Lord Byron

